title.narrative: IR 1.PROMOTION DES SIX PRATIQUES FAMILIA

description.narrative: At 31 December 2015 the rate of knowledge of six essential family practices (EFP) aiming to significantly reduce infant mortality has increased by 30% for each of these practices, which contributes to Cross-Sectoral Adolescent Development, Cross-Sectoral Communication For Development, Immunization, Polio Eradication. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By the end of 2015, 40 per cent of men and women adopt the six key family practices (exclusive breastfeeding, sleeping under insecticide-treated mosquito nets, handwashing with soap, treatment of diarrhoea using ORS, PMTCT of HIV, and complementary infant feeding) for child survival and development, with at least a 30 per cent increase in each practice nationwide.
